t Condition\n- Healthy rice plants are bright green and upright.\n- Diseased plants show mixed green and yellow-brown coloration.\n- Growth may appear weak compared to healthy neighboring plants.\n\nHow To Identify BLB From Images\n--------------------------------\n\nKey Indicators:\n- Yellowing begins from leaf tips or edges.\n- Long linear lesions extending along leaf veins.\n- Brown or burnt leaf tips.\n- Gradual transition from green → yellow → brown.\n- Drying pattern follows the length of the leaf.\n- Presence of multiple infected leaves in the same cluster.\n\nFeatures That Strongly Suggest BLB:\n- Elongated streak-like lesions.\n- Straw-colored drying.\n- Leaf margin infection.\n- Burnt appearance on upper leaf portions.\n- Symptoms aligned with leaf structure.\n\nFeatures That Are NOT Typical BLB\n---------------------------------\n- Circular spots with dark rings.\n- Powdery white fungal coating.\n- Random holes caused by insects.\n- Uniform yellowing of entire plant without lesions.\n- Healthy grain heads with no leaf symptoms.\n\nEnvironmental Context\n---------------------\n- Common in wet rice fields.\n- Often appears after heavy rain, standing water, or strong wind damage.\n- Spreads faster in humid environments.\n- Frequently observed in dense rice cultivation.\n\nImage Annotation Guidance For AI Training\n-----------------------------------------\nWhen labeling images:\n- Focus on leaf discoloration patterns.\n- Capture lesion direction and shape.\n- Include close-up views of infected tips and margins.\n- Preserve natural field background when possible.\n- Ensure disease symptoms are clearly visible under natural light.\n\nImportant AI Detection Features\n-------------------------------\nThe AI model should learn:\n- Color transition patterns.\n- Longitudinal lesion structure.\n- Burnt leaf-tip appearance.\n- Mixed healthy and diseased leaf regions.\n- Disease progression along leaf length.\n- Texture difference between healthy and infected tissue.\