(553, 'Tillering', 'image_bank/Tillering_338.jpg', 'Tillering_338.jpg', 'Tillering Stage in Rice - Brief Description\n===========================================\n\nOverview\n--------\nTillering is an important vegetative growth stage in rice plants where multiple side shoots, called tillers, emerge from the base of the main stem.\nEach tiller can later develop into a productive stem capable of producing grain.\n\nVisual Characteristics\n----------------------\n- Multiple green shoots emerge from the lower base of the plant.\n- Rice plants appear dense and bushy.\n- Leaves are long, narrow, upright, and bright green.\n- No grain heads or panicles are visible.\n- The field usually appears thick with green vegetation.\n\nIdentification Clues\n--------------------\n- Several stems growing from one plant base.\n- Strong vegetative growth.\n- Healthy green coloration.\n- Occurs before flowering and grain development.\n\nImportance\n----------\n- Higher tiller numbers can increase grain yield potential.\n- Proper water and nutrient supply during this stage is important.\n\nAI Training Notes\n-----------------\nImportant features for AI detection:\n- Multiple shoots from a single base.\n- Dense green canopy.\n- Absence of grains or panicles.\n- Upright leaf structure.\n\nConclusion\n----------\nThe tillering stage is recognized by active vegetative growth and the formation of multiple shoots from the base of the rice plant before reproductive stages begin.', 512, 1, '2026-05-08 12:39:41.105658', '2026-05-08 12:39:41.838202', 4, 2),
(554, 'Tillering', 'image_bank/Tillering_339.jpg', 'Tillering_339.jpg', 'Tillering Stage in Rice - Brief Description\n===========================================\n\nOverview\n--------\nTillering is an important vegetative growth stage in rice plants where multiple side shoots, called tillers, emerge from the base of the main stem.\nEach tiller can later develop into a productive stem capable of producing grain.\n\nVisual Characteristics\n----------------------\n- Multiple green shoots emerge from the lower base of the plant.\n- Rice plants appear dense and bushy.\n- Leaves are long, narrow, upright, and bright green.\n- No grain heads or panicles are visible.\n- The field usually appears thick with green vegetation.\n\nIdentification Clues\n--------------------\n- Several stems growing from one plant base.\n- Strong vegetative growth.\n- Healthy green coloration.\n- Occurs before flowering and grain development.\n\nImportance\n----------\n- Higher tiller numbers can increase grain yield potential.\n- Proper water and nutrient supply during this stage is important.\n\nAI Training Notes\n-----------------\nImportant features for AI detection:\n- Multiple shoots from a single base.\n- Dense green canopy.\n- Absence of grains or panicles.\n- Upright leaf structure.\n\nConclusion\n----------\nThe tillering stage is recognized by active vegetative growth and the formation of multiple shoots from the base of the rice plant before reproductive stages begin.', 512, 1, '2026-05-08 12:39:41.875766', '2026-05-08 12:39:42.577539', 4, 2),
(555, 'Milking_stage', 'image_bank/Milking_stage_1.jpg', 'Milking_stage_1.jpg', 'Milking Stage in Rice - Brief Description\n========================================\n\nOverview\n--------\nThe milking stage is a reproductive growth stage in rice where grains inside the panicle begin filling with a soft, milky fluid.\nThis stage occurs after flowering and before grain hardening.\n\nVisual Characteristics\n----------------------\n- Visible rice panicles or grain heads are present.\n- Grains are green, soft, and immature.\n- When pressed, grains release a white milky liquid.\n- Leaves are still mostly green but may start showing slight aging or drying.\n- Plants remain upright with developing grain clusters.\n\nIdentification Clues\n--------------------\n- Presence of grain-filled panicles.\n- Soft developing grains instead of hard mature seeds.\n- Green to light yellow coloration in the crop.\n- Occurs after flowering but before ripening.\n\nImportance\n----------\n- This is a critical grain-filling stage.\n- Proper water and nutrient supply strongly affect final yield.\n- Stress or disease during this stage can reduce grain quality and production.\n\nAI Training Notes\n-----------------\nImportant features for AI detection:\n- Clearly visible panicles.\n- Developing green grains.\n- Dense grain clusters hanging from stems.\n- Combination of leafy vegetation and grain formation.\n- No fully mature golden-yellow grains yet.\n\nConclusion\n----------\nThe milking stage is identified by the presence of soft, developing rice grains filled with milky fluid inside visible panicles before the grains fully mature and harden.', 512, 1, '2026-05-08 12:40:10.750493', '2026-05-08 12:40:11.115916', 4, 3),
(556, 'Milking_stage', 'image_bank/Milking_stage_2.jpg', 'Milking_stage_2.jpg', 'Milking Stage in Rice - Brief Description\n========================================\n\nOverview\n--------\nThe milking stage is a reproductive growth stage in rice where grains inside the panicle begin filling with a soft, milky fluid.\nThis stage occurs after flowering and before grain hardening.\n\nVisual Characteristics\n----------------------\n- Visible rice panicles or grain heads are present.\n- Grains are green, soft, and immature.\n- When pressed, grains release a white milky liquid.\n- Leaves are still mostly green but may start showing slight aging or drying.\n- Plants remain upright with developing grain clusters.\n\nIdentification Clues\n--------------------\n- Presence of grain-filled panicles.\n- Soft developing grains instead of hard mature seeds.\n- Green to light yellow coloration in the crop.\n- Occurs after flowering but before ripening.\n\nImportance\n----------\n- This is a critical grain-filling stage.\n- Proper water and nutrient supply strongly affect final yield.\n- Stress or disease during this stage can reduce grain quality and production.\n\nAI Training Notes\n-----------------\nImportant features for AI detection:\n- Clearly visible panicles.\n- Developing green grains.\n- Dense grain clusters hanging from stems.\n- Combination of leafy vegetation and grain formation.\n- No fully mature golden-yellow grains yet.\n\nConclusion\n----------\nThe milking stage is identified by the presence of soft, developing rice grains filled with milky fluid inside visible panicles before the grains fully mature and harden.', 512, 1, '2026-05-08 12:40:11.124031', '2026-05-08 12:40:11.486465', 4, 3),
