ms.\n- Infection often appears scattered initially, then spreads across nearby plants.\n- Lower and middle canopy leaves may also show symptoms in severe cases.\n\n6. Plant Condition\n- Healthy rice plants are bright green and upright.\n- Diseased plants show mixed green and yellow-brown coloration.\n- Growth may appear weak compared to healthy neighboring plants.\n\nHow To Identify BLB From Images\n--------------------------------\n\nKey Indicators:\n- Yellowing begins from leaf tips or edges.\n- Long linear lesions extending along leaf veins.\n- Brown or burnt leaf tips.\n- Gradual transition from green → yellow → brown.\n- Drying pattern follows the length of the leaf.\n- Presence of multiple infected leaves in the same cluster.\n\nFeatures That Strongly Suggest BLB:\n- Elongated streak-like lesions.\n- Straw-colored drying.\n- Leaf margin infection.\n- Burnt appearance on upper leaf portions.\n- Symptoms aligned with leaf structure.\n\nFeatures That Are NOT Typical BLB\n---------------------------------\n- Circular spots with dark rings.\n- Powdery white fungal coating.\n- Random holes caused by insects.\n- Uniform yellowing of entire plant without lesions.\n- Healthy grain heads with no leaf symptoms.\n\nEnvironmental Context\n---------------------\n- Common in wet rice fields.\n- Often appears after heavy rain, standing water, or strong wind damage.\n- Spreads faster in humid environments.\n- Frequently observed in dense rice cultivation.\n\nImage Annotation Guidance For AI Training\n-----------------------------------------\nWhen labeling images:\n- Focus on leaf discoloration patterns.\n- Capture lesion direction and shape.\n- Include close-up views of infected tips and margins.\n- Preserve natural field background when possible.\n- Ensure disease symptoms are clearly visible under natural light.\n\nImportant AI Detection Features\n-------------------------------\nThe AI model should learn:\n- Color transition patterns.\n- Longitudinal lesion structure.\n- Burnt leaf-tip appearance.\n- Mixed healthy and diseased leaf regions.\n- Disease progression along leaf length.\n- Texture difference between healthy and infected tissue.\n\nConclusion\n----------\nBacterial Leaf Blight is visually characterized by elongated yellow-to-brown lesions, burnt leaf tips, and progressive drying \nalong rice leaves. The disease typically follows the natural vein direction of the leaf and creates a distinct linear damage pattern \nthat differentiates it from many fungal spots or insect-related damage.\n\nProvide a full advisory: confirm what this likely is, then explain causes, treatment, and prevention. If the visual match is low confidence, say so.', 'It looks like your rice plants have Bacterial Leaf Blight (BLB). This disease causes yellowing and long, narrow brown lesions on the leaves, starting from the tips. \n\n**Causes:**\n- It is caused by a bacterium that thrives in humid, waterlogged conditions.\n- Heavy rain or standing water can worsen the problem.\n\n**Treatment:**\n- Remove and destroy infected leaves to prevent spreading.\n- Use a copper-based fungicide as per the instructions on the label.\n- Apply it during dry weather for better effectiveness.\n\n**Prevention:**\n- Ensure proper drainage in your fields to avoid waterlogging.\n- Space plants properly to improve air circulation.\n- Rotate crops and avoid planting rice in the same field year after year.\n\nKeep an eye on your plants and act quickly if you see symptoms again!', 'It looks like your rice plants have Bacterial Leaf Blight (BLB). This disease causes yellowing and long, narrow brown lesions on the leaves, starting from the tips. \n\n**Causes:**\n- It is caused by a bacterium that thrives in humid, waterlogged conditions.\n- Heavy rain or standing water can worsen the problem.\n\n**Treatment:**\n- Remove and destroy infected leaves to prevent spreading.\n- Use a copper-based fungicide as per the instructions on the label.\n- Apply it during dry weather for better effectiveness.\n\n**Prevention:**\n- Ensure proper drainage in your fields to avoid waterlogging.\n- Space plants properly to improve air circulation.\n- Rotate crops and avoid planting rice in the same field year after year.\n\nKeep an eye on your plants and act quickly if you see symptoms again!', '', 10.83, '', '{\"steps\": [{\"stage\": \"translate_in\", \"ms\": 0}, {\"stage\": \"classify\", \"ms\": 2812}, {\"stage\": \"retrieve\", \"ms\": 3282, \"hits\": 6}, {\"stage\": \"generate\", \"ms\": 4733, \"persona\": \"farmer\"}, {\"stage\": \"translate_out\", \"ms\": 0}], \"user_type\": \"farmer\", \"image_query\": {\"matched_prefix\": \"bacterial_leaf_blight\", \"matched_description\": \"Bacterial Leaf Blight (BLB) in Rice - Detailed AI Training Description\\n======================================================================\\n\\nOverview\\n--------\\nBacterial Leaf Blight (BLB) is a serious rice plant disease commonly caused by the bacterium Xanthomonas oryzae pv. oryzae. \\nThe disease mainly affects rice leaves and causes visible discoloration, drying, and elongated lesions. \\nIt is commonly observed in humid and waterlogged paddy fields.\\n\\nVisual Characteristics\\n----------------------\\n\\n1. Leaf Color Changes\\n- Leaves begin showing pale green to yellow discoloration.\\n- Yellowing usually starts near the leaf tip or along leaf margins.\\n- The infected area gradually spreads downward along the leaf blade.\\n- Advanced infection turns yellow areas into straw-colored or light brown regions.\\n\\n2. Lesion Appearance\\n- Lesions are long, narrow, and linear.\\n- They follow the natural direction of the leaf veins.\\n- The edges of lesions may appear wavy or irregular.\\n- Lesions often start at th\", \"matched_image_url\": \"/media/image_bank/bacterial_leaf_blight_1.jpg\", \"distance\": 1.7881393432617188e-07, \"score\": 1.0, \"low_confidence\": false}}', 'Responded', 0, '', 4, NULL, NULL),
(75, '2026-05-08 12:49:40.308663', '', '', '', 'Others', 'Management Advice', 'Milking stage management', '', 'Flowering', 'variety, land type', '[IMAGE QUERY]', 'English', '', 'A farmer uploaded an image. The visual most closely matches the topic \'Milking stage\'. Visual description: Milking Stage in Rice - Brief Description\n========================================\n\nOverview\n--------\nThe milking stage is a reproductive growth stage in rice where grains inside the panicle begin filling with a soft, milky fluid.\nThis stage occurs after flowering and before grain hardening.\n\nVisual Characteristics\n----------------------\n- Visible rice panicles or grain heads are present.\n- Grains are green, soft, and immature.\n- When pressed, grains release a white milky liquid.\n- Leaves are still mostly green but may start showing slight aging or drying.\n- Plants remain upright with developing grain clusters.\n\nIdentification Clues\n--------------------\n- Presence of grain-filled panicles.\n- Soft developing grains instead of hard mature seeds.\n- Green to light yellow coloration in the crop.\n- Occurs after flowering but before ripening.\n\nImportance\n----------\n- This is a critical grain-filling stage.\n- Proper water and nutrient supply strongly affect final yield.\n- Stress or disease during this stage can reduce grain quality and production.\n\nAI Training Notes\n-----------------\nImportant features for AI detection:\n- Clearly visible panicles.\n- Developing green grains.\n- Dense grain clusters hanging from stems.\n- Combination of leafy vegetation and grain formation.\n- No fully mature golden-yellow grains yet.\n\nConclusion\n----------\nThe milking stage is identified by the presence of soft, developing rice grains filled with milky fluid inside visible panicles before the grains fully mature and harden.\n\nProvide a full advisory: confirm what this likely is, then explain causes, treatment, and prevention. If the visual match is low confidence, say so.', '### Confirmation of Milking Stage in Rice\n\nBased on the provided visual description, it is highly likely that the observed stage in the rice crop is indeed the **milking stage**. This reproductive growth phase is characterized by the presence of soft, immature grains filled with a milky fluid, which aligns with the visual characteristics mentioned.\n\n### Causes of Milking Stage Characteristics\n\nThe milking stage occurs after flowering and is critical for grain development. The following factors contribute to the successful progression through this stage:\n\n- **Water Availability**: Adequate irrigation is essential, especially during the reproductive phase. Water stress can lead to poor grain filling.\n- **Nutrient Supply**: Sufficient nitrogen (N), phosphorus (P), and potassium (K) are crucial for optimal growth. A deficiency can hinder grain development.\n- **Temperature**: Optimal temperatures (around 25-30°C) promote healthy grain filling. Extreme temperatures can adversely affect the process.\n- **Pest and Disease Pressure**: Infestations by pests (e.g., stem borers) or diseases (e.g., blast disease caused by Magnaporthe oryzae) can impact grain development.\n\n### Treatment and Management Strategies\n\nTo ensure the rice crop successfully transitions through the milking stage, the following treatments and management strategies should be employed:\n\n1. **Water Management**:\n   - **Irrigation**: Ensure consistent water supply, especially if rainfall is insufficient. Irrigate the crop if water stress is observed.\n   - **Bund Strengthening**: Collect and retain rainwater by reinforcing bunds to prevent water loss.\n\n2. **Nutrient Management**:\n   - **Fertilizer Application**: Apply a balanced fertilizer regimen:\n     - Basal application of full P and K, and 25% of N at planting.\n     - Top dress with 50% of N at 15 days after planting and 25% at panicle initiation.\n   - **Foliar Nutrients**: Consider foliar applications of micronutrients if deficiencies are suspected.\n\n3. **Pest and Disease Control**:\n   - **Monitoring**: Regularly scout for pests and diseases. Implement integrated pest management (IPM) strategies.\n   - **Chemical Control**: Use appropriate insecticides or fungicides as needed, following local guidelines and recommendations.\n\n4. **Environmental Management**:\n   - **Temperature Regulation**: If possible, implement practices to mitigate extreme temperatures, such as mulching to retain soil moisture and regulate temperature.\n\n### Prevention Strategies\n\nTo prevent issues during the milking stage, consider the following proactive measures:\n\n- **Soil Health**: Maintain soil fertility through crop rotation and organic amendments to enhance microbial activity and nutrient availability.\n- **Water Conservation**: Implement water-saving technologies such as drip irrigation or alternate wetting and drying (AWD) to optimize water use.\n- **Resistant Varieties**: Use rice varieties that are known for their resilience to pests, diseases, and environmental stresses.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nThe milking stage is a critical period for rice development, and proper management of water, nutrients, and pest pressures is essential to maximize yield and grain quality. By implementing the recommended treatments and preventive measures, farmers can enhance the productivity of their rice crops during this vital growth phase.', '### Confirmation of Milking Stage in Rice\n\nBased on the provided visual description, it is highly likely that the observed stage in the rice crop is indeed the **milking stage**. This reproductive growth phase is characterized by the presence of soft, immature grains filled with a milky fluid, which aligns with the visual characteristics mentioned.\n\n### Causes of Milking Stage Characteristics\n\nThe milking stage occurs after flowering and is critical for grain development. The following factors contribute to the successful progression through this stage:\n\n- **Water Availability**: Adequate irrigation is essential, especially during the reproductive phase. Water stress can lead to poor grain filling.\n- **Nutrient Supply**: Sufficient nitrogen (N), phosphorus (P), and potassium (K) are crucial for optimal growth. A deficiency can hinder grain development.\n- **Temperature**: Optimal temperatures (around 25-30°C) promote healthy grain filling. Extreme temperatures can adversely affect the process.\n- **Pest and Disease Pressure**: Infestations by pests (e.g., stem borers) or diseases (e.g., blast disease caused by Magnaporthe oryzae) can impact grain development.\n\n### Treatment and Management Strategies\n\nTo ensure the rice crop successfully transitions through the milking stage, the following treatments and management strategies should be employed:\n\n1. **Water Management**:\n   - **Irrigation**: Ensure consistent water supply, especially if rainfall is insufficient. Irrigate the crop if water stress is observed.\n   - **Bund Strengthening**: Collect and retain rainwater by reinforcing bunds to prevent water loss.\n\n2. **Nutrient Management**:\n   - **Fertilizer Application**: Apply a balanced fertilizer regimen:\n     - Basal application of full P and K, and 25% of N at planting.\n     - Top dress with 50% of N at 15 days after planting and 25% at panicle initiation.\n   - **Foliar Nutrients**: Consider foliar applications of micronutrients if deficiencies are suspected.\n\n3. **Pest and Disease Control**:\n   - **Monitoring**: Regularly scout for pests and diseases. Implement integrated pest management (IPM) strategies.\n   - **Chemical Control**: Use appropriate insecticides or fungicides as needed, following local guidelines and recommendations.\n\n4. **Environmental Management**:\n   - **Temperature Regulation**: If possible, implement practices to mitigate extreme temperatures, such as mulching to retain soil moisture and regulate temperature.\n\n### Prevention Strategies\n\nTo prevent issues during the milking stage, consider the following proactive measures:\n\n- **Soil Health**: Maintain soil fertility through crop rotation and organic amendments to enhance microbial activity and nutrient availability.\n- **Water Conservation**: Implement water-saving technologies such as drip irrigation or alternate wetting and drying (AWD) to optimize water use.\n- **Resistant Varieties**: Use rice varieties that are known for their resilience to pests, diseases, and environmental stresses.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nThe milking stage is a critical period for rice development, and proper management of water, nutrients, and pest pressures is essential to maximize yield and grain quality. By implementing the recommended treatments and preventive measures, farmers can enhance the productivity of their rice crops during this vital growth phase.', '', 14.03, '', '{\"steps\": [{\"stage\": \"translate_in\", \"ms\": 0}, {\"stage\": \"classify\", \"ms\": 2844}, {\"stage\": \"retrieve\", \"ms\": 1217, \"hits\": 6}, {\"stage\": \"generate\", \"ms\": 9937, \"persona\": \"researcher\"}, {\"stage\": \"translate_out\", \"ms\": 0}], \"user_type\": \"researcher\", \"image_query\": {\"matched_prefix\": \"Milking_stage\", \"matched_description\": \"Milking Stage in Rice - Brief Description\\n========================================\\n\\nOverview\\n--------\\nThe milking stage is a reproductive growth stage in rice where grains inside the panicle begin filling with a soft, milky fluid.\\nThis stage occurs after flowering and before grain hardening.\\n\\nVisual Characteristics\\n----------------------\\n- Visible rice panicles or grain heads are present.\\n- Grains are green, soft, and immature.\\n- When pressed, grains release a white milky liquid.\\n- Leaves are still mostly green but may start showing slight aging or drying.\\n- Plants remain upright with developing grain clusters.\\n\\nIdentification Clues\\n--------------------\\n- Presence of grain-filled panicles.\\n- Soft developing grains instead of hard mature seeds.\\n- Green to light yellow coloration in the crop.\\n- Occurs after flowering but before ripening.\\n\\nImportance\\n----------\\n- This is a critical grain-filling stage.\\n- Proper water and nutrient supply strongly affect final yield.\\n- Stress or disease dur\", \"matched_image_url\": \"/media/image_bank/Milking_stage_11.jpg\", \"distance\": 0.17517458000764063, \"score\": 0.8248, \"low_confidence\": false}}', 'Responded', 0, '', 4, NULL, NULL),
(76, '2026-05-08 13:07:56.228720', '', '', '', 'Disease', 'Diagnosis', 'Bacterial Leaf Blight', '', '', '', 'What is Bacterial Leaf Blight?', 'English', '', 'What is Bacterial Leaf Blight?', 'Bacterial Leaf Blight (BLB) is a disease that affects rice plants. It causes yellowing and wilting of leaves, starting from the tips and edges. If you see these symptoms, it\'s important to manage the disease by using resistant rice varieties and practicing good field hygiene. Make sure to remove infected plants and avoid overcrowding in your fields.', 'Bacterial Leaf Blight (BLB) is a disease that affects rice plants. It causes yellowing and wilting of leaves, starting from the tips and edges. If you see these symptoms, it\'s important to manage the disease by using resistant rice varieties and practicing good field hygiene. Make sure to remove infected plants and avoid overcrowding in your fields.', '', 6.56, '', '{\"steps\": [{\"stage\": \"translate_in\", \"ms\": 0}, {\"stage\": \"classify\", \"ms\": 2780}, {\"stage\": \"retrieve\", \"ms\": 953, \"hits\": 6}, {\"stage\": \"generate\", \"ms\": 2812, \"persona\": \"farmer\"}, {\"stage\": \"translate_out\", \"ms\": 0}], \"user_type\": \"farmer\"}', 'Responded', 0, '', 4, NULL, NULL),
(77, '2026-05-08 13:08:33.658905', '', '', '', 'Disease', 'Diagnosis', 'Bacterial Leaf Blight', '', '', '', 'What is Bacterial Leaf Blight?', 'English', '', 'What is Bacterial Leaf Blight?', '### Bacterial Leaf Blight (BLB) Overview\n\n**Definition**: Bacterial Leaf Blight (BLB) is a significant foliar disease affecting rice (Oryza sativa) caused primarily by the bacterium *Xanthomonas oryzae* pv. *oryzae*. This pathogen leads to substantial yield losses in rice production worldwide.\n\n### Symptoms\n\n- **Initial Symptoms**: The disease typically manifests as water-soaked lesions on the leaves, which can be mistaken for other issues such as nutrient deficiencies or environmental stress.\n- **Progression**: As the disease progresses, these lesions enlarge and turn yellow, eventually leading to necrosis. The affected areas may dry out and become brown, resulting in \"blighted\" leaves.\n- **Affected Leaves**: Symptoms often appear first on older leaves, and the disease can spread rapidly under favorable conditions, leading to significant defoliation.\n\n### Pathogen Characteristics\n\n- **Causative Agent**: *Xanthomonas oryzae* pv. *oryzae* is a gram-negative bacterium that thrives in warm, humid environments.\n- **Transmission**: The pathogen is primarily spread through infected seeds, water, and contaminated tools or equipment.\n\n### Resistance and Management\n\n- **Resistance**: Some rice varieties exhibit moderate resistance to BLB, which can be an effective management strategy. For instance, certain specialty rice varieties have shown moderate resistance to BLB while also being resistant to other diseases such as rice tungro disease (RTD), sheath rot, neck blast, and brown spot.\n- **Cultural Practices**: Effective management strategies include crop rotation, proper water management, and the use of resistant varieties. Additionally, maintaining plant health through adequate nutrient management can help mitigate the impact of BLB.\n\n### Yield Impact\n\n- **Yield Losses**: BLB can lead to significant reductions in yield potential, with losses varying based on the severity of the outbreak and the susceptibility of the rice variety. The disease can also affect grain quality, leading to lower milling percentages and increased chalkiness in grains.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nBacterial Leaf Blight is a critical disease in rice production that requires integrated management strategies to minimize its impact. Continued research into resistant varieties and effective cultural practices is essential for sustainable rice cultivation. \n\n**References**: \n- [Source: Speciality rice]', '### Bacterial Leaf Blight (BLB) Overview\n\n**Definition**: Bacterial Leaf Blight (BLB) is a significant foliar disease affecting rice (Oryza sativa) caused primarily by the bacterium *Xanthomonas oryzae* pv. *oryzae*. This pathogen leads to substantial yield losses in rice production worldwide.\n\n### Symptoms\n\n- **Initial Symptoms**: The disease typically manifests as water-soaked lesions on the leaves, which can be mistaken for other issues such as nutrient deficiencies or environmental stress.\n- **Progression**: As the disease progresses, these lesions enlarge and turn yellow, eventually leading to necrosis. The affected areas may dry out and become brown, resulting in \"blighted\" leaves.\n- **Affected Leaves**: Symptoms often appear first on older leaves, and the disease can spread rapidly under favorable conditions, leading to significant defoliation.\n\n### Pathogen Characteristics\n\n- **Causative Agent**: *Xanthomonas oryzae* pv. *oryzae* is a gram-negative bacterium that thrives in warm, humid environments.\n- **Transmission**: The pathogen is primarily spread through infected seeds, water, and contaminated tools or equipment.\n\n### Resistance and Management\n\n- **Resistance**: Some rice varieties exhibit moderate resistance to BLB, which can be an effective management strategy. For instance, certain specialty rice varieties have shown moderate resistance to BLB while also being resistant to other diseases such as rice tungro disease (RTD), sheath rot, neck blast, and brown spot.\n- **Cultural Practices**: Effective management strategies include crop rotation, proper water management, and the use of resistant varieties. Additionally, maintaining plant health through adequate nutrient management can help mitigate the impact of BLB.\n\n### Yield Impact\n\n- **Yield Losses**: BLB can lead to significant reductions in yield potential, with losses varying based on the severity of the outbreak and the susceptibility of the rice variety. The disease can also affect grain quality, leading to lower milling percentages and increased chalkiness in grains.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nBacterial Leaf Blight is a critical disease in rice production that requires integrated management strategies to minimize its impact. Continued research into resistant varieties and effective cultural practices is essential for sustainable rice cultivation. \n\n**References**: \n- [Source: Speciality rice]', '', 17.97, '', '{\"steps\": [{\"stage\": \"translate_in\", \"ms\": 0}, {\"stage\": \"classify\", \"ms\": 2796}, {\"stage\": \"retrieve\", \"ms\": 907, \"hits\": 6}, {\"stage\": \"generate\", \"ms\": 14250, \"persona\": \"researcher\"}, {\"stage\": \"translate_out\", \"ms\": 0}], \"user_type\": \"researcher\"}', 'Responded', 0, '', 4, NULL, NULL),
(78, '2026-05-08 14:44:39.143830', '', '', '', 'Disease', 'Diagnosis', 'Bacterial Leaf Blight', '', '', 'variety, land type, season, crop stage', '[IMAGE QUERY]', 'English', '', 'What is bacterial leaf blight, and what should be done about it? (Identified visually from an uploaded image. Visual signs: Bacterial Leaf Blight (BLB) in Rice - Detailed AI Training Description\n======================================================================\n\nOverview\n--------\nBacterial Leaf Blight (BLB) is a serious rice plant disease commonly caused by the bacterium Xanthomonas oryzae pv. oryzae. \nThe disease mainly affects rice leaves and causes visible discoloration, drying, and elongated lesions. \nIt is commonly observed in humid and waterlogged paddy fields.\n\nVisual Characteristics\n----------------------\n\n1. Leaf Color Changes\n- Leaves begin showing pale green to yellow discoloration.\n- Yellowing usually starts near the leaf tip or along leaf margins.\n- The infected area gradually spreads downward along the leaf blade.\n- Advanced infection turns yellow areas into straw-colored or light brown regions.\n\n2. Lesion Appearance\n- Lesions are long, narrow, and linear.\n- They follow the natural direction of the leaf veins.\n- The edges of lesions may appear wavy or irregular.\n- Lesions often start at the leaf tip and extend toward the base.\n- In severe infection, the entire leaf becomes dry and burnt-looking.\n\n3. Drying Pattern\n- Tips of leaves appear dry and brown.\n- Drying progresses from tip to lower portions.\n- Severely infected leaves curl slightly and lose firmness.\n- Dead tissue becomes thin, papery, and brittle.\n\n4. Texture and Surface Details\n- Infected portions lose healthy glossy green appearance.\n- Diseased areas appear dull, dry, and faded.\n- Water-soaked streaks may appear during early infection stages.\n- Small droplets or bacterial ooze can sometimes appear in humid conditions.\n\n5. Disease Distribution\n- Multiple leaves in the same plant may show similar symptoms.\n- Infection often appears scattered initially, then spreads across nearby plants.\n- Lower and middle canopy leaves may also show symptoms in severe cases.\n\n6. Plant Condition\n- Healthy rice plants are bright green and upright.\n- Diseased plants show mixed green and yellow-brown coloration.\n- Growth may appear weak compared to healthy neighboring plants.\n\nHow To Identify BLB From Images\n--------------------------------\n\nKey Indicators:\n- Yellowing begins from leaf tips or edges.\n- Long linear lesions extending along leaf veins.\n- Brown or burnt leaf tips.\n- Gradual transition from green → yellow → brown.\n- Drying pattern follows the length of the leaf.\n- Presence of multiple infected leaves in the same cluster.\n\nFeatures That Strongly Suggest BLB:\n- Elongated streak-like lesions.\n- Straw-colored drying.\n- Leaf margin infection.\n- Burnt appearance on upper leaf portions.\n- Symptoms aligned with leaf structure.\n\nFeatures That Are NOT Typical BLB\n---------------------------------\n- Circular spots with dark rings.\n- Powdery white fungal coating.\n- Random holes caused by insects.\n- Uniform yellowing of entire plant without lesions.\n- Healthy grain heads with no leaf symptoms.\n\nEnvironmental Context\n---------------------\n- Common in wet rice fields.\n- Often appears after heavy rain, standing water, or strong wind damage.\n- Spreads faster in humid environments.\n- Frequently observed in dense rice cultivation.\n\nImage Annotation Guidance For AI Training\n-----------------------------------------\nWhen labeling images:\n- Focus on leaf discoloration patterns.\n- Capture lesion direction and shape.\n- Include close-up views of infected tips and margins.\n- Preserve natural field background when possible.\n- Ensure disease symptoms are clearly visible under natural light.\n\nImportant AI Detection Features\n-------------------------------\nThe AI model should learn:\n- Color transition patterns.\n- Longitudinal lesion structure.\n- Burnt leaf-tip appearance.\n- Mixed healthy and diseased leaf regions.\n- Disease progression along leaf length.\n- Texture difference between healthy and infected tissue.\n\nConclusion\n----------\nBacterial Leaf Blight is visually characterized by elongated yellow-to-brown lesions, burnt leaf tips, and progressive drying \nalong rice leaves. The disease typically follows the natural vein direction of the leaf and creates a distinct linear damage pattern \nthat differentiates it from many fungal spots or insect-related damage.)', 'I cannot provide an answer without the visual context or specific details about the symptoms you see in your rice plants. Please describe the symptoms or share the visual signs you have observed.', 'I cannot provide an answer without the visual context or specific details about the symptoms you see in your rice plants. Please describe the symptoms or share the visual signs you have observed.', '', 10.31, '', '{\"steps\": [{\"stage\": \"translate_in\", \"ms\": 0}, {\"stage\": \"classify\", \"ms\": 4250}, {\"stage\": \"retrieve\", \"ms\": 2156, \"hits\": 6}, {\"stage\": \"generate\", \"ms\": 3890, \"persona\": \"farmer\"}, {\"stage\": \"translate_out\", \"ms\": 0}], \"user_type\": \"farmer\", \"image_query\": {\"matched_prefix\": \"bacterial_leaf_blight\", \"matched_description\": \"Bacterial Leaf Blight (BLB) in Rice - Detailed AI Training Description\\n======================================================================\\n\\nOverview\\n--------\\nBacterial Leaf Blight (BLB) is a serious rice plant disease commonly caused by the bacterium Xanthomonas oryzae pv. oryzae. \\nThe disease mainly affects rice leaves and causes visible discoloration, drying, and elongated lesions. \\nIt is commonly observed in humid and waterlogged paddy fields.\\n\\nVisual Characteristics\\n----------------------\\n\\n1. Leaf Color Changes\\n- Leaves begin showing pale green to yellow discoloration.\\n- Yellowing usually starts near the leaf tip or along leaf margins.\\n- The infected area gradually spreads downward along the leaf blade.\\n- Advanced infection turns yellow areas into straw-colored or light brown regions.\\n\\n2. Lesion Appearance\\n- Lesions are long, narrow, and linear.\\n- They follow the natural direction of the leaf veins.\\n- The edges of lesions may appear wavy or irregular.\\n- Lesions often start at th\", \"matched_image_url\": \"/media/image_bank/bacterial_leaf_blight_1.jpg\", \"distance\": 1.7881393432617188e-07, \"score\": 1.0, \"low_confidence\": false}}', 'Responded', 0, '', 4, NULL, NULL),
(79, '2026-05-08 15:30:11.220414', '', '', '', 'Disease', 'Diagnosis', 'Bacterial Leaf Blight', '', '', '', 'What is Bacterial Leaf Blight?', 'English', '', 'What is Bacterial Leaf Blight?', 'Bacterial Leaf Blight (BLB) is a disease that affects rice plants. It causes yellowing and wilting of leaves, which can lead to lower yields. To manage it, keep your field clean, use resistant rice varieties, and apply recommended pesticides if needed. If you see symptoms, act quickly to protect your crop.', 'Bacterial Leaf Blight (BLB) is a disease that affects rice plants. It causes yellowing and wilting of leaves, which can lead to lower yields. To manage it, keep your field clean, use resistant rice varieties, and apply recommended pesticides if needed. If you see symptoms, act quickly to protect your crop.', '', 15.7, '', '{\"steps\": [{\"stage\": \"translate_in\", \"ms\": 0}, {\"stage\": \"classify\", \"ms\": 5750}, {\"stage\": \"retrieve\", \"ms\": 6796, \"hits\": 6}, {\"stage\": \"generate\", \"ms\": 3110, \"persona\": \"farmer\"}, {\"stage\": \"translate_out\", \"ms\": 0}], \"user_type\": \"farmer\"}', 'Responded', 0, '', 4, NULL, NULL),
