(82, '2026-05-08 15:49:27.073202', '', '', '', 'Disease', 'Diagnosis', 'unknown disease', '', 'Milking', 'variety, symptoms, environmental conditions', '[IMAGE QUERY] What disease this plant has?', 'English', '', 'The user uploaded an image (visually identified as \'Milking stage\', signs: Milking Stage in Rice - Brief Description\n========================================\n\nOverview\n--------\nThe milking stage is a reproductive growth stage in rice where grains inside the panicle begin filling with a soft, milky fluid.\nThis stage occurs after flowering and before grain hardening.\n\nVisual Characteristics\n----------------------\n- Visible rice panicles or grain heads are present.\n- Grains are green, soft, and immature.\n- When pressed, grains release a white milky liquid.\n- Leaves are still mostly green but may start showing slight aging or drying.\n- Plants remain upright with developing grain clusters.\n\nIdentification Clues\n--------------------\n- Presence of grain-filled panicles.\n- Soft developing grains instead of hard mature seeds.\n- Green to light yellow coloration in the crop.\n- Occurs after flowering but before ripening.\n\nImportance\n----------\n- This is a critical grain-filling stage.\n- Proper water and nutrient supply strongly affect final yield.\n- Stress or disease during this stage can reduce grain quality and production.\n\nAI Training Notes\n-----------------\nImportant features for AI detection:\n- Clearly visible panicles.\n- Developing green grains.\n- Dense grain clusters hanging from stems.\n- Combination of leafy vegetation and grain formation.\n- No fully mature golden-yellow grains yet.\n\nConclusion\n----------\nThe milking stage is identified by the presence of soft, developing rice grains filled with milky fluid inside visible panicles before the grains fully mature and harden.) and asked: \"What disease this plant has?\". Answer the user\'s question using this visual context.', 'I can\'t tell if your rice plant has a disease just from the description of the milking stage. However, during this stage, it\'s important to watch for signs of stress, such as yellowing leaves or wilting. If you see any unusual spots, discoloration, or pests, those could indicate a problem. Please check for these signs and let me know what you observe.', 'I can\'t tell if your rice plant has a disease just from the description of the milking stage. However, during this stage, it\'s important to watch for signs of stress, such as yellowing leaves or wilting. If you see any unusual spots, discoloration, or pests, those could indicate a problem. Please check for these signs and let me know what you observe.', '', 11.48, '', '{\"steps\": [{\"stage\": \"translate_in\", \"ms\": 0}, {\"stage\": \"classify\", \"ms\": 4734}, {\"stage\": \"retrieve\", \"ms\": 2984, \"hits\": 6}, {\"stage\": \"generate\", \"ms\": 3765, \"persona\": \"farmer\"}, {\"stage\": \"translate_out\", \"ms\": 0}], \"user_type\": \"farmer\", \"image_query\": {\"matched_prefix\": \"Milking_stage\", \"matched_description\": \"Milking Stage in Rice - Brief Description\\n========================================\\n\\nOverview\\n--------\\nThe milking stage is a reproductive growth stage in rice where grains inside the panicle begin filling with a soft, milky fluid.\\nThis stage occurs after flowering and before grain hardening.\\n\\nVisual Characteristics\\n----------------------\\n- Visible rice panicles or grain heads are present.\\n- Grains are green, soft, and immature.\\n- When pressed, grains release a white milky liquid.\\n- Leaves are still mostly green but may start showing slight aging or drying.\\n- Plants remain upright with developing grain clusters.\\n\\nIdentification Clues\\n--------------------\\n- Presence of grain-filled panicles.\\n- Soft developing grains instead of hard mature seeds.\\n- Green to light yellow coloration in the crop.\\n- Occurs after flowering but before ripening.\\n\\nImportance\\n----------\\n- This is a critical grain-filling stage.\\n- Proper water and nutrient supply strongly affect final yield.\\n- Stress or disease dur\", \"matched_image_url\": \"/media/image_bank/Milking_stage_11.jpg\", \"distance\": 0.17517458000764063, \"score\": 0.8248, \"low_confidence\": false}}', 'Responded', 0, '', 4, NULL, NULL),
(83, '2026-05-08 15:50:12.545512', '', '', '', 'Disease', 'Diagnosis', 'Bacterial Leaf Blight', '', '', '', '[IMAGE QUERY] What disease this plant has?', 'English', '', 'The user uploaded an image (visually identified as \'bacterial leaf blight\', signs: Bacterial Leaf Blight (BLB) in Rice - Detailed AI Training Description\n======================================================================\n\nOverview\n--------\nBacterial Leaf Blight (BLB) is a serious rice plant disease commonly caused by the bacterium Xanthomonas oryzae pv. oryzae. \nThe disease mainly affects rice leaves and causes visible discoloration, drying, and elongated lesions. \nIt is commonly observed in humid and waterlogged paddy fields.\n\nVisual Characteristics\n----------------------\n\n1. Leaf Color Changes\n- Leaves begin showing pale green to yellow discoloration.\n- Yellowing usually starts near the leaf tip or along leaf margins.\n- The infected area gradually spreads downward along the leaf blade.\n- Advanced infection turns yellow areas into straw-colored or light brown regions.\n\n2. Lesion Appearance\n- Lesions are long, narrow, and linear.\n- They follow the natural direction of the leaf veins.\n- The edges of lesions may appear wavy or irregular.\n- Lesions often start at the leaf tip and extend toward the base.\n- In severe infection, the entire leaf becomes dry and burnt-looking.\n\n3. Drying Pattern\n- Tips of leaves appear dry and brown.\n- Drying progresses from tip to lower portions.\n- Severely infected leaves curl slightly and lose firmness.\n- Dead tissue becomes thin, papery, and brittle.\n\n4. Texture and Surface Details\n- Infected portions lose healthy glossy green appearance.\n- Diseased areas appear dull, dry, and faded.\n- Water-soaked streaks may appear during early infection stages.\n- Small droplets or bacterial ooze can sometimes appear in humid conditions.\n\n5. Disease Distribution\n- Multiple leaves in the same plant may show similar symptoms.\n- Infection often appears scattered initially, then spreads across nearby plants.\n- Lower and middle canopy leaves may also show symptoms in severe cases.\n\n6. Plant Condition\n- Healthy rice plants are bright green and upright.\n- Diseased plants show mixed green and yellow-brown coloration.\n- Growth may appear weak compared to healthy neighboring plants.\n\nHow To Identify BLB From Images\n--------------------------------\n\nKey Indicators:\n- Yellowing begins from leaf tips or edges.\n- Long linear lesions extending along leaf veins.\n- Brown or burnt leaf tips.\n- Gradual transition from green → yellow → brown.\n- Drying pattern follows the length of the leaf.\n- Presence of multiple infected leaves in the same cluster.\n\nFeatures That Strongly Suggest BLB:\n- Elongated streak-like lesions.\n- Straw-colored drying.\n- Leaf margin infection.\n- Burnt appearance on upper leaf portions.\n- Symptoms aligned with leaf structure.\n\nFeatures That Are NOT Typical BLB\n---------------------------------\n- Circular spots with dark rings.\n- Powdery white fungal coating.\n- Random holes caused by insects.\n- Uniform yellowing of entire plant without lesions.\n- Healthy grain heads with no leaf symptoms.\n\nEnvironmental Context\n---------------------\n- Common in wet rice fields.\n- Often appears after heavy rain, standing water, or strong wind damage.\n- Spreads faster in humid environments.\n- Frequently observed in dense rice cultivation.\n\nImage Annotation Guidance For AI Training\n-----------------------------------------\nWhen labeling images:\n- Focus on leaf discoloration patterns.\n- Capture lesion direction and shape.\n- Include close-up views of infected tips and margins.\n- Preserve natural field background when possible.\n- Ensure disease symptoms are clearly visible under natural light.\n\nImportant AI Detection Features\n-------------------------------\nThe AI model should learn:\n- Color transition patterns.\n- Longitudinal lesion structure.\n- Burnt leaf-tip appearance.\n- Mixed healthy and diseased leaf regions.\n- Disease progression along leaf length.\n- Texture difference between healthy and infected tissue.\n\nConclusion\n----------\nBacterial Leaf Blight is visually characterized by elongated yellow-to-brown lesions, burnt leaf tips, and progressive drying \nalong rice leaves. The disease typically follows the natural vein direction of the leaf and creates a distinct linear damage pattern \nthat differentiates it from many fungal spots or insect-related damage.) and asked: \"What disease this plant has?\". Answer the user\'s question using this visual context.', 'Your rice plants have Bacterial Leaf Blight (BLB). Look for these signs:\n\n- Yellowing starts from the leaf tips or edges.\n- Long, narrow lesions that follow the leaf veins.\n- Brown or burnt tips on the leaves.\n- Leaves may appear dry and curled.\n- Multiple leaves on the same plant show similar symptoms.\n\nIt\'s important to manage this disease quickly to protect your crop.', 'Your rice plants have Bacterial Leaf Blight (BLB). Look for these signs:\n\n- Yellowing starts from the leaf tips or edges.\n- Long, narrow lesions that follow the leaf veins.\n- Brown or burnt tips on the leaves.\n- Leaves may appear dry and curled.\n- Multiple leaves on the same plant show similar symptoms.\n\nIt\'s important to manage this disease quickly to protect your crop.', '', 7.72, '', '{\"steps\": [{\"stage\": \"translate_in\", \"ms\": 0}, {\"stage\": \"classify\", \"ms\": 3046}, {\"stage\": \"retrieve\", \"ms\": 1358, \"hits\": 6}, {\"stage\": \"generate\", \"ms\": 3266, \"persona\": \"farmer\"}, {\"stage\": \"translate_out\", \"ms\": 0}], \"user_type\": \"farmer\", \"image_query\": {\"matched_prefix\": \"bacterial_leaf_blight\", \"matched_description\": \"Bacterial Leaf Blight (BLB) in Rice - Detailed AI Training Description\\n======================================================================\\n\\nOverview\\n--------\\nBacterial Leaf Blight (BLB) is a serious rice plant disease commonly caused by the bacterium Xanthomonas oryzae pv. oryzae. \\nThe disease mainly affects rice leaves and causes visible discoloration, drying, and elongated lesions. \\nIt is commonly observed in humid and waterlogged paddy fields.\\n\\nVisual Characteristics\\n----------------------\\n\\n1. Leaf Color Changes\\n- Leaves begin showing pale green to yellow discoloration.\\n- Yellowing usually starts near the leaf tip or along leaf margins.\\n- The infected area gradually spreads downward along the leaf blade.\\n- Advanced infection turns yellow areas into straw-colored or light brown regions.\\n\\n2. Lesion Appearance\\n- Lesions are long, narrow, and linear.\\n- They follow the natural direction of the leaf veins.\\n- The edges of lesions may appear wavy or irregular.\\n- Lesions often start at th\", \"matched_image_url\": \"/media/image_bank/bacterial_leaf_blight_1.jpg\", \"distance\": 1.7881393432617188e-07, \"score\": 1.0, \"low_confidence\": false}}', 'Responded', 0, '', 4, NULL, NULL);
